Fuzzy black bee with two yellow stripes, one on the head and one near the rear. Translucent black wings.
There were two nests of these bees behind a fence overlooking Almaden Lake. The nests were underground and covered with bark chips. There was a lot of activity around the nest as bees came and went. Unfortunately, most were too fast for my camera to capture. 
There is a hillside covered with wildflowers below the nests and the bees would come back to the nest fully loaded with orange pollen from the flowers.
They didn't seem to care that we were observing them so closely.

description:
I spotted this Yellow-faced Bumblebee (Bombus vosensenskii) working a large patch of Rose Clover (Trifolium hirtum) at Russian Ridge Open Space Preserve, and I found myself following it and attempting to take its picture.  The shots that came out reasonably well remind me of "Where's Waldo" pictures, with the bee playing the part of Waldo.

The best of these shots is the lead photo.  Here, the Yellow-faced Bumblebee came close enough for me to take a reasonably decent close-up photo of it, one that fortuitously shows the diagnostic yellow patch on its face. The California Bumblebee (Bombus californicus) is very similar in size and appearance, but lacks this yellow facial patch.

The lead photo also shows the yellow band on its thorax, its eyes (one on either side of the yellow face patch), its antenna (emerging from the yellow face patch), and - if you look carefully - a bit of its tongue, which it is inserting into the corolla tube of an individual clover flower for a sip of nectar. Also visible are its two front legs.

In the remaining two shots,the bee is partly to mostly obscured by the clover.  In Shot 2, you can see the side of the bee's head, which again shows part of the yellow facial patch extending over the crown and just touching the yellow band on its thorax. In Shot 3, the bee is facing away from the camera, so you can easily see its abdomen and semi-translucent wings.

Photographed near the main (Alpine Road) trailhead to the Rodge Trail at Russian Ridge Open Space Preserve in San Mateo County, CA.
place_guess: Russian Ridge Open Space Preserve, CA, US

description: California Bumblebee (Bombus californicus), photographed along the Stevens Creek Trail in Mountain View, CA.  I was surprised to see this bumblebee appear amongst the small cloud of Yellow-faced Bumblebees (Bombus vosnesenskii) who were working the Wild Radish (Raphanus sativus) along the Stevens Creek Trail.  Interestingly, this one had no yellow on its face, which made me think immediately of the Californica Bumblebee.  I also noticed that it was significantly larger than the many Yellow-faced Bumblees.  That said, I don't have much experience in the field with B. californicus, so this identification could be wrong.

description: A Bumblebee (Bombus sp.) pollinating the flowers of some Pride of Madeira (Echium candicans) at Lick Mill Park in Santa Clara, CA.  The presence of yellow hairs on the topmost abdominal segment (terga T1) eliminates the area's most common bumble bee - Bombus vosnesenskii - which always has black hairs across this part of its abdomen.  However, this opens the door to several other species, and exact identification would require a better view of the specimen, whose abdomen and face are partially concealed by the flowers that the bee is pollinating.  Therefore I am leaving this one identified to genus only.
